v class=3D"css-do4pef"><div class=3D"css-bwikp3"><div class=3D"rc-RichText"=
><p><b>Margin of error</b> is a statistical term that represents the range =
of uncertainty or variability around an estimate or measurement. It quantif=
ies the degree of confidence we can have in the estimate's accuracy. When c=
onducting surveys or <a href=3D"https://www.coursera.org/articles/data-coll=
ection-methods" target=3D"_self" rel=3D"">collecting data</a>, surveying th=
e entire population is often not feasible or practical. Instead, a sample i=
s taken, and the results are used to make inferences about the larger popul=
ation. The margin of error helps to account for the potential discrepancy b=
etween the sample and the population, leading to more accurate findings fro=
m your <a href=3D"https://www.coursera.org/articles/data-analytics" target=
=3D"_self" rel=3D"">data analytics</a>.</p><p>
</p><p>For example, you may want to know if your customers would support a =
new product release, so you poll a sampling of your existing customer base =
through an <a href=3D"https://www.coursera.org/articles/shopify-exit-survey=
" target=3D"_self" rel=3D"">email survey</a>. Since this sampling does not =
include all of your customers, the margin of error would account for the pe=
rcentage of customers who may or may not agree with those surveyed.</p><p>
