</p><p>The margin of error is typically expressed as a plus or minus value,=
 indicating the range within which the true value is likely to fall. If a s=
urvey reports a margin of error of =C2=B13 percent, the results are believe=
d to be accurate within three percentage points in either direction. This m=
eans the true value could be three percent higher or three percent lower th=
an the reported estimate.</p><p>
</p><p>For example, if your poll found that 80 percent of surveyed customer=
s approved of a new product release with a margin of error of =C2=B13 perce=
nt, your actual value could range from 77 to 83. This range of values is kn=
own as the confidence interval and represents the degree of uncertainty or =
certainty in your estimate.</p><p>
</p><p>Data with a lower margin of error is more accurate and reliable than=
 data with a higher margin of error. All data chosen as a random sample wil=
l have some uncertainty; the margin of error explains how much.</p><p>
</p><div class=3D"rc-ArticleHighlight cds"><div class=3D"css-1jke4yk"><div =
class=3D"css-1t29d8p"><div class=3D"css-sekxls"><div><h3>How to calculate m=
argin of error</h3><p>You can calculate your margin of error in two ways, d=
epending on whether you are using population parameters or sample statistic=
s. Depending on your sample size and whether you know the population standa=
rd deviation, you will either use a z-score or a t-score as your critical v=
alue.</p><p>
</p><p>For population parameters:</p><p>Margin of error =3D Critical value =
x Standard deviation of the population</p><p>
</p><p>For sample statistics:</p><p>Margin of error =3D Critical value x St=
andard error of the sample</p></div></div></div><div class=3D"css-175sjpy">=
<div class=3D"css-i5ivod"><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://d3njjcbhbojbot.cloud=
front.net/api/utilities/v1/imageproxy/https://coursera_assets.s3.amazonaws.=
com/articles/purple-hash-pattern.svg?auto=3Dformat%2Ccompress&amp;dpr=3D2&a=
mp;blur=3D200&amp;px=3D8&amp;max-w=3D252" class=3D"css-3gbnhs"><div class=
=3D"lazyload-wrapper"><div class=3D"lazyload-placeholder"></div></div></div=
></div></div></div><p>
</p><h3>What impacts the margin of error?&nbsp;</h3><p>Three main factors w=
ill usually impact your margin of error: sample size, standard deviation, a=
nd confidence level. If any of those change, the margin of error will chang=
e with them.&nbsp;</p><p></p><p>
</p><ul><li><p><b>Sample size:</b> Your <a href=3D"https://www.coursera.org=
/articles/what-is-sample-size" target=3D"_self" rel=3D"">sample size</a> re=
fers to the number of people or other entities you include in your survey. =
A larger population sample is a more realistic representation of that popul=
ation, so it's more likely to be accurate.&nbsp;</p></li></ul><p>
</p><ul><li><p><b>Standard deviation: </b>The population's standard deviati=
on, or variability, measures how far apart data points are from one another=
. Larger deviations mean a larger margin of error, while smaller ones usual=
ly make for a smaller margin.&nbsp;</p></li></ul><p>
</p><ul><li><p><b>Confidence level:</b> Confidence level is a percentage th=
at shows how certain you are that your sample is representative of your ent=
ire population. Commonly used confidence levels are 90 percent, 95 percent,=
 and 99 percent. As the confidence level increases, the margin of error bec=
omes wider to capture a higher level of certainty. Conversely, if a lower c=
onfidence level is chosen, the margin of error will be narrower, indicating=
 a lower level of certainty.</p></li></ul><p></p><p>
</p><div class=3D"rc-ArticleHighlight cds"><div class=3D"css-1jke4yk"><div =
class=3D"css-1t29d8p"><div class=3D"css-sekxls"><div><h3>Are margin of erro=
r and sampling error the same?</h3><p>
</p><p>The margin of error is a summary of the sampling error, quantifying =
the uncertainty of your measurement. This sampling error accounts for the d=
ifference between our sample findings and the true population parameter.&nb=
sp;</p><p>
</p><p>Typically, you represent this sampling error as the margin of error,=
 denoted as =E2=80=9C+/-=E2=80=9D your margin of error. When you combine th=
is margin of error with your sample statistic, you create a confidence inte=
